<u>Equity spurring equality in the art world</u>
"Equality is typically defined as treating everyone the same and giving everyone </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">access to the same opportunities. Meanwhile, equity refers to proportional </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">representation (by race, class, gender, etc.)"</pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;"><br></pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;"><i>Disclaimer
</i>I don't know much/don't consider myself to be affiliated with the 'art community'</pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;"><i>Background</i>
Some art collections are setting quotas for artworks created by certain </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">underrepresented groups. E.g. an art fund is striving for 25% of their </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">acquisitions in the next couple years to be works produced by African American women.

<i>What this means:</i>
Some collectives in the 'art world' are trying to spur equality between majority </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">and underrepresented groups by artificially striving for equity (equal representation). </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">This push for equity effectively creates artificial demand for art produced by </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">underrepresented groups. Over time, as the risk in pursuing art fields for </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">these groups decreases and the artificial demand fueled by this push for </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">equity decreases (due to surplus of artworks), art will hopefully start to </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">be evaluated more evenly/independent of source; equality will be achieved in </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">the art community. Who knows when or if we'll converge to this point. </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">Many art conservatives and others are worried that these quotas are foolish </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">since they lower the objective bar for art accepted in certain collections/galleries </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">modernday. They also wonder whether such high quotas are even feasible; e.g. say a contemporary </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">collection with ~100k works is looking to fill 25% with African American women artists during the 50s. </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">While this push for equity is well intentioned, maybe research shows that there probably </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">aren't even close to enough works to fill this quota. </pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;">Does it make more sense to reduce risk and stigma pursuing art within certain groups instead?<br></pre><pre style="margin:0;margin-bottom:0; margin-top:0;"><br></pre>
